[2]
Date: 25 Aug 2005
From: A-lan Banks <A-Lan.Banks@thomson.com>
Source: New Indpress [edited]
<http://www.newindpress.com/NewsItems.asp?ID=IEH20050825073020&Page=H&Title=Top+Stories&Topic=0>

28 more cases of suspected Japanese encephalitis were reported from various
districts of Uttar Pradesh on Thursday [25 Aug 2005], taking the toll due
to the fatal brain fever to 185, Additional Director State Health Services
D P Mishra said.
He said Maharajganj and Kushinagar districts remained worst affected; 235
patients [from those areas have] so far been admitted to the medical
college [in Gorakhpur].
Among others admitted in the hospital, 200 were children, he said adding,
"On average, 40-50 patients were being admitted every day."
Hospitals around the state have been asked to take measures such as
anti-larval treatment, indoor spray and fogging, and isolated wards have
been set up for treatment of encephalitis patients.
