[4]
Date: 25 Aug 2005
From: Cat Bachman <catbachman@yahoo.com>
Source: Newkerala.com, 22 Aug 2005 [edited]
<http://www.newkerala.com/news.php?action=fullnews&id=15944>

Japanese encephalitis has spread from eastern Uttar Pradesh to the capital
city [Lucknow] and several far-flung areas, claiming 158 lives in over 3
weeks. As many as 3 dozen children are under treatment at the children's
ward of King George's Medical University (KGMU), a fact that has only just
come to light.
"The patients were admitted a few days ago but it was only on Sunday [21
Aug 2005] that their diagnosis for Japanese encephalitis was confirmed,"
Ram Kant, the chief medical superintendent, admitted here Monday [22 Aug 2005].
State Health Director General O.P. Singh said the virus had spread to as
far as Chitrakoot in the southeastern corner of the state where 6 children
have died. Fatehpur in central Uttar Pradesh also reported some
deaths. The disease had initially hit Gorakhpur, Maharajganj, Kushinagar,
Bahraich, Barabanki, Lakhimpur-Kheri, Varanasi, Sitapur and Rae Bareli
districts.
"While the victims were mostly children, 8 adults have also succumbed to
the virus since it broke out on 29 Jul [2005]," Singh said.
This type of brain fever, which has been confirmed as Japanese encephalitis
by the National Institute of Infectious Diseases (NIID), has been a
perennial problem in large parts of eastern Uttar Pradesh, where the virus
has been striking consecutively for the past 27 years.
--
Cat Bachman
<catbachman@yahoo.com>
[Thanks to Cat Bachman for the valuable information. ProMED encourages all
its readers to submit reports of outbreaks from reliable sources. In this
report, the 1st official declaration of Japanese encephalitis through the
National Institute of Infectious Diseases (NIID) was documented.- Mod.RY]
[Encephalitis is an annual epidemic and a perennial problem in India. The
current outbreak is particularly serious due to the heavy onset of the
monsoon, which resulted in the worst flooding in the affected area in 27
years. So far the death toll of this outbreak has not only surpassed but
nearly quadrupled that of 2004. - Mod.RY]
